The current file calculates channels in four steps: pick P1, define the working window, derive a sloped midline, then place parallel rails around it. In session mode it scans enabled sessions, marks each session start, and uses the most recent detected session start as p1x/p1Off; in manual mode it finds the first bar at or before the chosen anchor time, and if neither resolves it falls back to 50 bars back.

Anchor logic
P1 comes from either the selected manual timestamp or the latest enabled session start found in the lookback scan, and the code stores both the bar index (p1x) and offset (p1Off) for that anchor. If nothing valid is found, it forces p1x = bar_index - 50 so the indicator still has a start point to work from.

Midline logic
Once P1 exists, the script sets xEnd to the smaller of the current bar and p1x + scanBars, then computes the midline slope from the price difference between close[p1Off] and the current close: slope = (close[0] - close[p1Off]) / (bar_index - p1x). The midline therefore starts at the P1 close and slopes toward the current close, with intercept = close[p1Off].

Width logic
Channel width is not currently found by a full wick-cluster search; instead, calcWidth() measures the maximum excursion above and below the P1 close across the P1-to-xEnd range, then takes the larger of those distances, with a minimum floor of syminfo.mintick * wickRoundTicks. In practice that means width is the furthest wick distance from the P1 close, not a statistically selected rail from repeated touches.

Inclusion checks
For every bar from p1x to xEnd, the script projects the midline, top rail, and bottom rail, then counts:

midline touches when a high or low is within midTouchTolTicks * syminfo.mintick,

inside bars when the whole candle body stays between the rails,

rail hits when the high is near the top rail or the low is near the bottom rail.

It then computes insidePct = insideCnt / (insideCnt + outsideCnt) * 100, but right now that percentage is only reported in debug output and is not used to reject or optimize channels, even though minInsidePct exists as an input.

